# mechanical keyboard picks
#
# current daily driver:
# - logitech g610 orion (cherry mx brown, white led, dedicated media keys)
#   bus 003 device 011: id 046d:c338 logitech, inc. gaming keyboard g610
#
# discontinued. notes here are for picking a replacement when it dies.


# what i actually like about the g610

# - no rgb
# - minimal backlight — just white
# - dedicated multimedia controls (mute, play, prev, next, volume roller)
# - cherry mx brown switches
# - full-size layout (numpad available even if rarely used)
# - wired connection (no battery, no bluetooth pairing, no surprises)


# what i could give up

# - the numpad. could likely live with a 75% / tkl.
# - tradeoff: most tkl / 75% boards drop dedicated media keys to fn-layer.
#   only full-size "professional" boards still ship a real media row.


# full-size replacements (matching all four criteria)

# the perfect fit:
# - das keyboard 6 pro
#   - cherry mx brown, white led only (no rgb), dedicated media row +
#     clickable volume knob, aluminum top, usb-c.
#   - essentially "the g610 made by a company that cares about looking
#     professional instead of gamer."
#   - lowest mental adjustment from current setup.

# compromise on one criterion:
# - das keyboard 4 professional
#   - drop the backlight; keep everything else.
#   - best-in-class media keys with the massive volume knob das is known for.
#   - the "if you don't actually need backlight" pick.
#
# - leopold fc900r pd (white led)
#   - drop dedicated media keys (fn-layer only).
#   - highest-build-quality keyboard on this list. korean-made, pbt keycaps
#     that won't shine like abs. "boring professional" aesthetic.
#   - the long-term-survivor pick.
#
# - varmilo va108m (white led)
#   - drop dedicated media keys (fn-layer).
#   - widest range of beautiful themed keycap sets, pbt keycaps. same build
#     philosophy as leopold.
#
# - keychron k10 pro (white led variant)
#   - drop dedicated media keys (volume knob + fn-layer media).
#   - hot-swappable switches (try different switches without buying a new
#     board). hybrid wired/wireless — works fine wired but you're paying for
#     a wireless module + battery you'll never use.
#   - the future-proofing pick if you accept the hybrid tax.


# tkl replacements (if dropping the numpad)

# - leopold fc750r pd (white led)
#   - tkl, white backlight, cherry mx brown, pbt keycaps, no rgb.
#   - "adult professional" tkl answer. media on fn layer.
#
# - varmilo va87m (white led)
#   - tkl, white backlight, cherry mx brown, gorgeous pbt keycap themes,
#     no rgb on white-led variants. media on fn layer.
#
# - keychron k8 pro (white led variant)
#   - tkl, hot-swappable, white backlight, cherry mx option, hybrid
#     wired/wireless. works fine wired-only.
#   - most "modern" choice; hot-swap means changing switches later without
#     re-buying.
#
# - keychron c3 pro (white led)
#   - tkl, WIRED-ONLY, gateron switches (not cherry mx), white backlight,
#     hot-swap on some variants. much cheaper than the k-series since you're
#     not paying for the wireless module.


# 75% replacements

# - keychron c3 pro (white led)
#   - wired-only 75% from keychron's wired line. gateron switches by default,
#     not cherry mx — so the switch feel is different even if "tactile brown."
#
# - keychron k2 v2 (white led)
#   - 75%, white backlight, cherry mx brown option, hybrid wired/wireless.
#     works fine wired-only.
#
# - keychron q2 / v2 (white led — stock varies)
#   - premium 75%, hot-swap. most q2s ship rgb; white-led variants are
#     limited.
#
# - niz plum 84
#   - 75%, white backlit, electrocapacitive (topre-style), not cherry mx.
#     different feel entirely. worth knowing about; probably not the answer.


# important tradeoffs

# dedicated media keys disappear at tkl. almost all tkl / 75% boards put
# media on an fn-layer (fn+f7/f8/f9 etc.) rather than dedicated buttons.
# the g610's standalone volume roller + media row is one of the things you
# give up with the smaller form factor. solvable with a small dedicated
# macropad or a knob like the 8bitdo retro mechanical knob that just does
# media.
#
# white-led-only boards are harder to find than they should be. most
# "premium mechanical" makers ship rgb by default and treat white-led as an
# afterthought. you have to specifically hunt the white-led sku.
#
# arrow cluster on 75% boards: the loss of arrow-cluster spacing on some
# 75% boards bothers people more than they expect. try one in a store
# before committing. tkl is the safer first step away from full-size.
#
# wired vs hybrid: das, leopold, varmilo are all wired-by-default — no
# tax for the wired preference. keychron's k / q series are hybrid
# wired/wireless (you pay for the wireless module + battery even if you
# never use them). if wired-only matters, drop to keychron's c-series
# (wired only, cheaper), or just plug in a k-series and ignore the
# bluetooth.


# the recommendations

# want "my g610 but slightly nicer":
# → das 6 pro. same ergonomics, same feature set, better materials.
#
# want "best-built full-size mechanical i can buy" (don't mind fn-layer media):
# → leopold fc900r pd. pbt keycaps + korean build quality. costs about the
#   same as the das.
#
# want future-proofing (swap switches later):
# → keychron k10 pro white-led. hot-swap is genuinely useful as taste evolves.
#   accept the hybrid wired/wireless tax, or downgrade to the wired-only
#   c-series and accept gateron switches instead of cherry.
#
# the das 6 pro is the only one with a dedicated media row exactly like the
# g610. if those buttons are non-negotiable, that narrows it to one.
#
# wired-only doesn't materially change the top picks: das 6 pro and leopold
# fc900r pd were already wired-by-default and remain the front-runners.
